<TR><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD>
<TD BACKGROUND="/black6.png">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5><TR><TD>
	<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=130 SRC="chocs/choc_day_12.png" ALT="chocolate"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=190 SRC="globes/advent_globe_12.png" ALT="snowglobe"><table cellpadding=10 align="center" background="/black4.png" width=430><TR><TD><center><font size=6 color="#ffff00"><b><i>BOARD GAMES</i></b></font><br><font size=3 color="red"><b><i>13 days to Christmas</i></b></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><p>
In the beginning was the board game, and that defined family
get-togethers in the early 80's. Whether it be huddling over the
dining table for an unavoidably epic game of <i>Monopoly</i>, or spending
late nights in the living room with a bowl of nibbles and a game of
the new-fangled <i>Trivial Pursuit</i>, it formed part of the backbone of
family games.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/2nr3gRJaVLM&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/2nr3gRJaVLM&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>A Look At BBC1 On Christmas Day 1984</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Including Les Dawson doing Blankety Blank - joy... <b><i>(1:58)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2nr3gRJaVLM" target="2nr3gRJaVLM">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

Of course, as I was ten at the most, and my brother not much older
than that, games of <i>Triv</i> seemed like banging your head against a brick
wall through general ignorance (at least, not without cheating
anyway), and the lack of business nous meant that <i>Monopoly</i> games went
on and on (and on...) where the winner was determined by luck rather
than judgement.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/647hE6n4Wzg&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/647hE6n4Wzg&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Put a Little Love in Your Heart / Annie Lennox and Al Green</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">A great song with subtle festive overtones. <b><i>(4:01)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=647hE6n4Wzg" target="647hE6n4Wzg">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
<i>Cluedo</i> was my favourite as the short game format and the nattily
designed miniature pieces made the game easier for the younger player
to really master. And having had my prepubescent arse dragged around
castle after castle after castle during family holidays, I could
actually discern some atmosphere from a game based inside a stately
home.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Enter the microchip. With board games becoming computerized, there was
immediately a huge elephant in the room: what exactly was the point?
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My family only ever went with one computerized board game, the
ubiquitous <i>Scrabble</i> game from Psion. It didn't last too long - unlike
real <i>Scrabble</i> where you can view your own rack of tiles any time you
<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=200 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d12_boardgames3.jpg" target="boardgames3.jpg"><IMG SRC="pngs/d12_boardgames3_small.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=256></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>And then there's Triv... I would carry on but I've been distracted by the Domino Rally that's on the same page - I got that actual set one Christmas and would set up domino tricks all around the house. Nowadays I keep meaning to build marble runs (kugelbahn) which offer similar amounts of excitement, but I think that's another project to delay until my retirement.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
like, with the computer version you had a choice of viewing it only
when it was your turn, or any time you like, so long as you don't mind
your own and all the other racks being visible at the same time.
Strategy kinda went out of the window as, the moment you saw someone
get a Q, the rest of you would hoard all the U's and blanks and only
use them in inaccessible places to the Q holder.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="left" WIDTH=200 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d12_boardgames2.jpg" target="boardgames2.jpg"><IMG SRC="pngs/d12_boardgames2_small.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=255></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>My neighbour had the PacMan board game, complete with hollow plastic ghosts and yellow PacMan which would actually scoop up the dots in the maze into its mouth.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
So, for games with friends and family, there was nothing better than
the real thing, which only left the humble Spec, which had the
endearing quality of often being rather stupid, and also believing
anything you would tell it.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Taking <i>Scrabble</i> as an example (a game in which the Spec rather sweetly
literally doesn't know the meaning of the word "FUN"), whenever you'd
play a word which wasn't in its dictionary, it would sternly challenge
you with a very grave "Are you sure (Y/N)?" As you'd just played with
the word "XHGD", you think it might have a point, but you press Y
anyway, only to get the response "Word Accepted"! Even better, in
later games before the computer is reset, the computer itself would
play "XHGD" as if it was the most natural thing in the world!
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Leisure Genius' <i>Scrabble Deluxe</i> would go one better, and actually make
up words and also use acronyms - I gave it a few choice words the
first time I saw it play "JATO" on a triple word score...
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With <i>Triv</i>, it's completely dumb - you never tell it any answers! The
computer merely asks you the questions, you press a key when you think
you have an answer, and the computer answers it for you before asking
if you got it right. Needless to say, I won many a game of Computer
Triv...
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="left" WIDTH=200 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d12_boardgames.jpg" target="boardgames.jpg"><IMG SRC="pngs/d12_boardgames_small.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=250></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>I had completely forgotten about Stay Alive, a sliding lever game where you hope to drop your opponent's balls through the holes before he does it to you.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/ZIUtowyTCKM&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/ZIUtowyTCKM&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Christmas 1985 Advert Break</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">All the favourites, including the traditional Christmas TV Times. Since deregulation yonks ago, the Christmas Radio Times is all you need during the holidays, the Christmas TV Times now reduced to being just an also-ran. <b><i>(2:48)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZIUtowyTCKM" target="ZIUtowyTCKM">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

What about the other two mainstays of family board games, <i>Monopoly</i> and
<i>Cluedo</i>? <i>Monopoly</i> has some tough computer players, until you realise
that they all suffer from a fatal flaw - they will do absolutely
anything in order to own a complete set. So, you buy a property in a
set, engineer your trades so that the target player owns the other
two, and then exchange your completing property for everything that
the computer player owns, minus the other properties in that set.
Within a few turns, that player is then well and truly bankrupt.
Occasionally you get the rather exciting outcome of a duopoly when it
all gets rather touch-and-go, but usually you end up wiping out all
the other computer players through their own greed.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As for <i>Cluedo</i>, the computer players, even at their toughest, are
ridiculously easy to beat. Not quite up to the level of the stupidity
found in <i>Battleships</i> where the computer player would bomb the crap out
of each vessel, and yet somehow miss out the odd obvious square, but
it comes close.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;But they all pass the time...
</TD></TR></TABLE><p>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
